Windows Communication Foundation (WCF) is a powerful technology that caters to a
range of platforms and protocols, ensuring smooth interoperability between
different systems.


CORE MECHANISMS FOR INTEROPERABILITY

 * WS-I Basic Profile Compliance: WCF is rooted in industry standards, allowing
   interconnection with various platforms and technologies.

 * Code Generation with WSDL: WCF generates service contracts from WSDL,
   supporting compatibility with non-WCF clients.

 * WS-Security Standards Adherence: By aligning with these standards, WCF
   enables secure data exchange across disparate systems.

 * Text Encoding Compatibility: WCF supports textual message encodings,
   facilitating interoperability with non-binary API services.

 * Multiple Transport Protocols: Straddling various transport mechanisms like
   HTTP, TCP, and MSMQ, WCF ensures agile platform-agnostic communication.


WCF INTEROPERABILITY CONFIGURATION EXAMPLE

Here is the C# code:

using System.ServiceModel;

[ServiceContract]
public interface IMyService
{
    [OperationContract]
    string GetData(int value);
}

public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public string GetData(int value)
    {
        return $"You entered: {value}";
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        using (var host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService), new Uri("http://localhost:8000/MyService")))
        {
            var endpoint = host.AddServiceEndpoint(typeof(IMyService), new BasicHttpBinding(), "");
            endpoint.Behaviors.Add(new WebHttpBehavior());

            host.Open();

            Console.WriteLine("The service is ready.");
            Console.WriteLine("Press <Enter> to stop the service.");
            Console.ReadLine();

            host.Close();
        }
    }
}

WCF's RESTful Service support Boston has become a popular choice for APIs with
its simplified design.


WCF AND REST

WCF introduces the WebHttpBinding that enables operations through several HTTP
verbs like GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE.

By using WebGet, WebInvoke, and the EnableWebScript behavior, WCF can be made to
work with traditional web constructs such as URIs and HTTP verbs.


ADVANTAGES

 * Simplicity: REST requires fewer protocols such as HTTP and JSON.

 * Scalability: REST systems can offer high scalability due to the stateless
   nature of the protocols.

 * Flexibility: RESTful methods, or "verbs", used in WCF are a subset of all
   HTTP methods, providing a focused resource-management mechanism.


CODE EXAMPLE: RESTFUL WCF SERVICE

Here is the C# code:

[ServiceContract]
public interface IMyService
{
    [OperationContract]
    [WebInvoke(Method = "POST", UriTemplate = "/data", ResponseFormat = WebMessageFormat.Json)]
    Data AddData(Data data);

    [OperationContract]
    [WebGet(UriTemplate = "/data/{id}", ResponseFormat = WebMessageFormat.Json)]
    Data GetData(string id);
}

public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public Data AddData(Data data) { /* Implementation */ }
    public Data GetData(string id) { /* Implementation */ }
}

public class Data
{
    public string Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

The WCF request-response service operation, also known as a Duplex Contract,
provides a two-way communication mechanism between the client and the service.

This bi-directional communication enables the service to invoke methods on the
client, making it suitable for applications like chat or interactive games.


WCF DUPLEX COMMUNICATION BASICS

 * Two-Way Communication: Unlike one-way operations, the duplex contract allows
   both the client and the service to initiate communication, forming a message
   exchange pattern or MEP of Request-Reply.
 * Instant Messaging Example: With duplex contracts, both ends - the client and
   service - behave like a peer, sending and receiving messages without waiting
   for a prompt from the other side.


CODE EXAMPLE: INSTANT MESSAGING SERVICE

// Service Contract
[ServiceContract(CallbackContract = typeof(IChatCallback))]
public interface IChatService
{
    [OperationContract]
    void JoinChatRoom(string username);

    [OperationContract(IsOneWay = true)]
    void SendMessage(string message);
}

// Callback Contract
public interface IChatCallback
{
    [OperationContract(IsOneWay = true)]
    void ReceiveMessage(string sender, string message);
}

// Service Implementation
public class ChatService : IChatService
{
    public Dictionary<IChatCallback, string> ConnectedClients = new Dictionary<IChatCallback, string>();

    public void JoinChatRoom(string username)
    {
        var connectedUser = OperationContext.Current.GetCallbackChannel<IChatCallback>();
        ConnectedClients[connectedUser] = username;
    }

    public void SendMessage(string message)
    {
        var sender = ConnectedClients.FirstOrDefault(client => client.Key == OperationContext.Current.GetCallbackChannel<IChatCallback>()).Value;

        foreach (var client in ConnectedClients.Where(c => c.Value != sender))
        {
            client.Key.ReceiveMessage(sender, message);
        }
    }
}

Instance management in WCF encompasses strategies for handling service objects,
their creation, and their lifetimes. It is crucial to optimize resource
utilization and support specific concurrency needs.


TECHNIQUES FOR EFFICIENT INSTANCE MANAGEMENT

SINGLETON

 * Description: A single service instance serves all client requests.

 * Use Case: When the object maintains state that multiple clients should
   access.

 * Code Example:

   WCF Service:

   [ServiceBehavior(InstanceContextMode = InstanceContextMode.Single)]
   public class MyService : IService { }


   Service Host:

   using (ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService)))
   {
       host.Open();
       Console.ReadLine();
   }


PERCALL

 * Description: Each client request creates a new service instance, independent
   of other client requests.

 * Use Case: When the object does not maintain state between client calls.

 * Code Example:

   WCF Service:

   [ServiceBehavior(InstanceContextMode = InstanceContextMode.PerCall)]
   public class MyService : IService { }


   Service Host:

   using (ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService)))
   {
       host.Open();
       Console.ReadLine();
   }


PERSESSION

 * Description: Each client session has a dedicated service instance, and all
   requests from the same client are handled within that instance.

 * Use Case: When the object maintains state that is unique to individual
   clients.

 * Code Example:

   WCF Service:

   [ServiceBehavior(InstanceContextMode = InstanceContextMode.PerSession)]
   public class MyService : IService { }


   Service Host:

   using (ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService)))
   {
       host.Open();
       Console.ReadLine();
   }

Instance modes in a WCF service define how the server manages its instance. This
determines whether the server maintains a single instance or creates a new one
for each client.


INSTANCE MODES

 1. Per-Call: Perfect for lightweight stateless operations, this mode creates a
    new instance for each client request. When the request is processed, the
    instance is disposed of.

 2. Per-Session: Similar to "Per-Call," but keeps the instance alive for the
    duration of a client session. The session ends when the client disconnects
    or when a timeout occurs.

 3. Singleton: This is the default for WCF services. A single instance is
    created for the entire lifetime of the service. Note that even in this mode,
    the WCF services may have multiple worker threads servicing the calls, which
    means it's up to the developer to ensure thread safety.


CODE EXAMPLE: INSTANCE MODES

Here is C# code:

[ServiceContract]
public interface IMyService
{
    [OperationContract]
    string GetData(int value);
}

[ServiceBehavior(InstanceContextMode = InstanceContextMode.PerCall)]
public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public string GetData(int value)
    {
        return string.Format("You entered: {0}", value);
    }
}

Throttling in WCF is the process of controlling the consumption of system
resources by regulating the rate at which operations execute. This is
particularly useful in multi-tenant systems where fair resource allocation is
important.


THROTTLING STRATEGIES

 * Concurrency Mode: Defines how operations are executed in relation to others.
   Options include "single", "multiple", and "reentrant".

 * Instance Context Mode: Dictates the lifespan of service instances, which
   affects resource usage.

 * Rate-based Throttling: Sets limits on the number of concurrent calls,
   sessions, or instances.


MECHANISMS FOR RATE-BASED THROTTLING

SERVICES, SESSIONS, AND INSTANCES

 * Service: Applies global rules to the service as a whole.

 * Per-session: Rules are specific to a session.

 * Context and Instance: Rules applied based on the context or instance of the
   service being used.

SERVICE BEHAVIORS

 * ServiceBehavior: Configures the service as a whole.

 * Contract Behavior: Applies behavior to a specific service contract.

 * Operation Behavior: Governs the behavior of a specific operation.

 * Endpoint Behavior: Affects an endpoint's behavior.


PROGRAMMATIC DESIGN FOR THROTTLING

The ServiceThrottlingBehavior class encapsulates throttling configuration, and
you can instantiate and configure it directly in your code.


PRACTICAL EXAMPLES

Let's look at a simple WCF service and its configurations for better
understanding.

Here is the code:

// Define the Service Contract
[ServiceContract]
public interface IMyService
{
    [OperationContract]
    string GetData(int value);

    [OperationContract]
    void ProcessData(string data);
}

// Implement the Service Contract
public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public string GetData(int value)
    {
        return $"You entered: {value}";
    }

    public void ProcessData(string data)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Processing data: {data}");
    }
}

// Host the Service
class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        using (ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService)))
        {
            // Enable Concurrency Mode
            var instanceContext = new InstanceContext(host, 10);
            host.ServiceType = typeof (MyService);
            host.Open();
            Console.WriteLine("The service is running on port : 8000");
            Console.Read();
        }
    }
}

WCF primarily supports three types of contracts: service contracts, data
contracts, and fault contracts, each serving distinct purposes.


SERVICE CONTRACTS

 * Purpose: Describes the operations that a service supports.
 * Attributes: Identified by the [ServiceContract] attribute.
 * Methods: Defined with [OperationContract] attribute and can be one-way or
   request-reponse depending on the parameters.

EXAMPLE

// Service Contract
[ServiceContract]
public interface ICalculatorService
{
    // Methods
    [OperationContract]
    double Add(double num1, double num2);
    [OperationContract(IsOneWay = true)]
    void StartProcess();
}



DATA CONTRACTS

 * Purpose: Defines data structures to be exchanged between the client and the
   service.
 * Attributes: Applied to classes/structs, denoted by [DataContract]. Members
   with [DataMember] attribute are serialized.
 * Nature: Can be simple types like integers or strings, or complex types
   defining more intricate data structures.

EXAMPLE

// Data Contract
[DataContract]
public class Employee
{
    // Member with DataMember
    [DataMember]
    public string Name { get; set; }
    [DataMember]
    public int EmployeeID { get; set; }
}



FAULT CONTRACTS

 * Purpose: Encompasses the errors or exceptions that can be raised by a
   service.
 * Attributes: Defined with [FaultContract] at the service contract level. The
   fault type needs to be declared with [DataContract] and [DataMember]
   attributes.

EXAMPLE

// Fault Contract
[ServiceContract]
public interface IShippingService
{
    [OperationContract]
    [FaultContract(typeof(ShippingFault))]
    void Ship(Product product);
}

// Fault Class
[DataContract]
public class ShippingFault
{
    [DataMember]
    public string Issue { get; set; }
}

While modifying a deployed WCF service contract  known as a "versioning"
operation  is possible, it's generally discouraged due to its complexities.


CONTRACT CHANGES AFTER DEPLOYMENT

 * Changing Service Contracts: Though technically feasible, modifying the
   service contract after deployment introduces compatibility and
   interoperability risks across consumers.
 * Versioning a Service Contract: It's best to create a new service contract,
   either from scratch or as a modified version of the original, and expose this
   contract as a separate endpoint to ensure smooth transitions for existing
   clients.


VERSIONING STRATEGIES

DUAL ENDPOINT

 * Strategy: Maintain both old and new service contract versions side by side on
   different service endpoints.
 * Best Used When: A clean, immediate cut-off from the old contract to the new
   version is feasible.
 * Implementation:

 ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService));
 host.AddServiceEndpoint(typeof(IOldContract), new BasicHttpBinding(), "Old");
 host.AddServiceEndpoint(typeof(INewContract), new BasicHttpBinding(), "New");
 ```

#### Adapter Pattern

- **Strategy**: Use a contraptionlike the Adapter Pattern to channel client calls across the old and new service contracts.
- **Best Used When**: There are numerous clients or an immediate cutover is impractical.
- **Risks**: Adds an extra layer of complexity.
- **Implementation**:

 - Service contract:

 ```csharp
 [ServiceContract]
 public interface INewContract
 {
     [OperationContract]
     void NewOperation();
 }
 ```

 - Client adapter:

 ```csharp
 public class ServiceAdapter : IOldContract
 {
     private INewContract newService;

     public ServiceAdapter()
     {
         newService = new NewContractClient();
     }

     public void OldOperation()
     {
         newService.NewOperation();
     }
 }
 ```

 - Host:

 ```csharp
 ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService));
 host.AddServiceEndpoint(typeof(IOldContract), new BasicHttpBinding(), "Adapter");
 host.AddServiceEndpoint(typeof(INewContract), new BasicHttpBinding(), "New").EndpointBehaviors.Add(new WebHttpBehavior());
 ```

#### Publish-Subscribe

- **Strategy**: Employ a messaging pattern where clients subscribe to specific communication types ("events").
- **Best Used When**: There is a need to support a prolonged overlap between the old and new contracts.
- **Risks**: Introduces an extra layer of asynchronous communication that might be unnecessary for simple operations.
- **Components**: **Publishers** are the service providers. **Subscribers** are the clients.
- **Libraries**: For .NET-based WCF services, the `System.ServiceModel` namespace encapsulates the needed functionality.

### Recommended Approaches

- **Shared Language**: Keep verbiage consistent across contracts to facilitate users' understanding and adoption.
- **Enforce Clear Deployment Phases** where service providers roll out new versions and deprecate the older ones.

In Windows Communication Foundation (WCF), behaviors are key in modifying the
default nature of services and clients. Such modifications extend to endpoints,
services, and data contracts.


TYPES OF BEHAVIORS

 1. Service Behaviors: Apply to the complete service and control its runtime
    behavior.
 2. Endpoint Behaviors: Get applied to individual endpoints and adjust
    communication settings.
 3. Contract Behaviors: Influence the behavior of service operations.


CORE MODIFICATIONS BROUGHT ABOUT BY BEHAVIORS

 * Instancing Mode: Controls how service instances are managed (e.g., per-call,
   per-session).
 * Concurrency Mode: Determines how multiple threads interact with service
   instances.
 * Service Throttling: Manages the number of concurrent calls that are allowed.
 * Transactions: Specifies transaction attributes at the service level.
 * Error Handling: Centralizes exception management at the service level.
 * Metadata: Customizes metadata publishing for the service.


CODE EXAMPLE: SERVICE BEHAVIOR

Here is the C# code:

using System.ServiceModel;

// Service Contract
[ServiceContract]
public interface IMyService
{
    [OperationContract]
    string GetData(int value);
}

// Service class
public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public string GetData(int value) => string.Format("You entered: {0}", value);
}

// Service behavior attribute
[ServiceBehavior(InstanceContextMode = InstanceContextMode.Single, ConcurrencyMode = ConcurrencyMode.Multiple)]
public class Program
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService));
        host.Open();
        Console.WriteLine("The service is ready.");
        Console.ReadLine();
        host.Close();
    }
}


In this example, we configure the InstanceContextMode and ConcurrencyMode using
the ServiceBehavior attribute.


CODE EXAMPLE: ENDPOINT BEHAVIOR

Below is the C# code:

// Define behavior
public class MyEndpointBehavior : IEndpointBehavior
{
    public void AddBindingParameters(ServiceEndpoint endpoint, BindingParameterCollection bindingParameters)
    {
        // Implement as needed
    }

    public void ApplyDispatchBehavior(ServiceEndpoint endpoint, EndpointDispatcher endpointDispatcher)
    {
        // Implement as needed
    }

    public void ApplyClientBehavior(ServiceEndpoint endpoint, ClientRuntime clientRuntime)
    {
        // Implement as needed
    }

    public void Validate(ServiceEndpoint endpoint)
    {
        // Implement as needed
    }
}

// Configure behavior for an endpoint
ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService));
ServiceEndpoint endpoint = host.AddServiceEndpoint(typeof(IMyService), new BasicHttpBinding(), "MyService");
endpoint.EndpointBehaviors.Add(new MyEndpointBehavior());

Certificate-based security in Windows Communication Foundation (WCF) leverages
digital certificates to secure communication channels. This mechanism guarantees
the identity of parties involved and encrypts data.


KEY CONCEPTS

 * Certificates: Also called public key certificates, these files contain a
   public key and are often issued by a Certificate Authority (CA).
 * Public/Private Key Pair: A cryptographic technique where data encrypted with
   one key requires the other key to decrypt. Only the intended recipient should
   have the private key.
 * Digital Signature: A hashed message, encrypted with a private key, that
   verifies the identity of the sender and ensures data integrity.


HOW IT WORKS

 1. Certificate Acquisition: Each party must obtain a digital certificate.

 2. Certificate Exchange: This can be either direct or through a CA:

    * Direct Exchange: Manually exchange certificates between parties.
    * CA: Certificates are obtained from a trusted Certificate Authority.

 3. Certificate Validation: Before starting a secure channel, validity and trust
    of the certificates are checked.

 4. Channel Negotiation: Based on negotiated security algorithms, an SSL session
    is established using exchanged certificates.

 5. Data Exchange: All communication after the channel establishment is
    encrypted.

 6. Security Levels & Options: WCF offers three security levels  None,
    Transport, and Message. Each level enforces a certain set of security
    features.

    * None: No security is enforced.
    * Transport: Encrypts the channel but doesn't sign individual messages.
    * Message: Each message gets signed and optionally encrypted.


CODE EXAMPLE: ADDING CERTIFICATES TO A WCF SERVICE

Here is the C# code:

// Define the ServiceContract
[ServiceContract]
public interface IMyService
{
    [OperationContract]
    string MyMethod(string data);
}

// Implement the ServiceContract
public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public string MyMethod(string data)
    {
        return "You entered: " + data;
    }
}

// Host the service
static void Main()
{
    using (ServiceHost host = new ServiceHost(typeof(MyService)))
    {
        // Security settings for the service
        host.Credentials.ServiceCertificate.SetCertificate(
            StoreLocation.LocalMachine,
            StoreName.My,
            X509FindType.FindBySubjectName,
            "MyServer"
        );

        // Start the host
        host.Open();
        Console.WriteLine("Service is running...");
        Console.ReadLine();
    }
}

A Fault Contract in WCF is a contractual agreement that allows developers to
define and handle service-based exceptions across service boundaries. It enables
the service to communicate the nature of a fault via a specific defined
exception.


ROLE AND BENEFITS

In a service-oriented architecture:

 * Clear Communication: Identifies defined faults, making exception handling
   more transparent for client applications.
 * Interoperability: Ensures predictable behavior in cross-platform or
   cross-technology scenarios.
 * Design Consistency: Ensures that all parts of a service adhere to the same
   fault-handling mechanism.
 * Code Integrity: Helps avoid potential mismatched or unhandled exceptions.
 * Security and Reliability: Enables robust, controlled error reporting


IMPLEMENTATION STEPS

 1. Define a Fault Contract: Repeated in both the service interface and the
    actual exception class.

 2. Throw a Fault Exception: When the service encounters an error that warrants
    a fault rather than a standard exception.

 3. Handle the Fault: Clients can anticipate and process faults without
    interrupting the service operation response.


CODE EXAMPLE: CALCULATOR SERVICE

Here is the C# code:

[ServiceContract]
public interface ICalculatorService
{
    [OperationContract]
    [FaultContract(typeof(DivideByZeroException))]
    int Divide(int numerator, int denominator);
}

public class CalculatorService : ICalculatorService
{
    public int Divide(int numerator, int denominator)
    {
        if (denominator == 0)
        {
            var fault = new FaultException<DivideByZeroException>(new DivideByZeroException());
            throw fault;
        }

        return numerator / denominator;
    }
}

Windows Communication Foundation (WCF) provides tools to pass service errors and
custom error data to clients. This is primarily achieved through
FaultException<TDetail>, which supports detailed error information transmission
to clients.


KEY CONCEPTS

FAULTEXCEPTION

 * FaultException is designed to transmit service errors to clients.
 * FaultException<TDetail> extends this functionality by allowing the passing of
   user-defined error details.

OPERATIONCONTRACT FAULTCONTRACT

 * OperationContract can be adorned with FaultContract, specifying that a method
   can return custom fault exceptions.


WCF CODE EXAMPLE: PASSING USER-DEFINED ERROR DATA

Here is the C# code:

Service Contract:

[ServiceContract]
public interface IDataService
{
    [OperationContract]
    [FaultContract(typeof(DataRequestFault))]
    DataResult RetrieveData();
}

[DataContract]
public class DataRequestFault
{
    [DataMember]
    public string FaultMessage { get; set; }
}

[DataContract]
public class DataResult
{
    [DataMember]
    public string DataDescription { get; set; }
}


Service Implementation:

public class DataService : IDataService
{
    public DataResult RetrieveData()
    {
        // Perform data retrieval and potentially encounter an error
        if (errorCondition)
        {
            var fault = new DataRequestFault { FaultMessage = "Data retrieval failed." };
            throw new FaultException<DataRequestFault>(fault, "Data retrieval error");
        }

        return new DataResult { DataDescription = "Data retrieved successfully." };
    }
}


Client-Side Handling:

try
{
    var result = client.RetrieveData();
    Console.WriteLine(result.DataDescription);
}
catch (FaultException<DataRequestFault> ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Error message: {ex.Detail.FaultMessage}");
    // Other error handling if needed
}
catch (FaultException ex)
{
    // Non-specific fault handling
}
catch (CommunicationException)
{
    // Communication issues
}



SUMMARY

Through FaultException<TDetail>, WCF enables the transmission of user-defined
error data from the service to the client, empowering more accurate error
handling.

WCF clients offer two approaches to exception management:

 * Fault Contracts: Allows you to define specific faults for the service to
   propagate.
 * Exception Handling and Fault Service: Offers end-to-end exception flow and
   more controlled client behavior.


1. FAULT CONTRACTS

Fault Contracts provide a structured way to propagate exceptions across service
boundaries, ensuring consistency in handling and enabling detailed feedback for
WCF and non-WCF clients.

For this method, Service and Operation Contracts can be decorated with the
FaultContract attribute. The client, in turn, should expect these custom-fault
messages.

CODE EXAMPLE: DEFINING A FAULT CONTRACT AND HANDLING IN CLIENT

Here are the C# code:

[ServiceContract]
public interface IMyService
{
    [OperationContract]
    [FaultContract(typeof(MyServiceFault))]
    void DoWork();
}

public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public void DoWork()
    {
        throw new FaultException<MyServiceFault>(new MyServiceFault("Service fault occurred!"));
    }
}

[DataContract]
public class MyServiceFault
{
    [DataMember]
    public string Message { get; set; }

    public MyServiceFault(string message)
    {
        Message = message;
    }
}

public class WcfClient
{
    public void CallServiceIMethod(string endpointUrl)
    {
        using (ServiceProxy<IMyService> proxy = new ServiceProxy<IMyService>(endpointUrl))
        {
            try
            {
                proxy.Channel.DoWork();
            }
            catch (FaultException<MyServiceFault> ex)
            {
                HandleMyServiceFault(ex.Detail);
            }
        }
    }

    public void HandleMyServiceFault(MyServiceFault fault)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Service Fault Message: " + fault?.Message);
    }

}



Here are the Fault contract and handling code.

BENEFITS

 * Consistency and Structure: Enables unified exception handling across
   services.
 * Client Awareness: Provides predictability to the client by specifying
   expected faults.


2. EXCEPTION HANDLING AND FAULT SERVICE

 * Exception Shielding: Allows the service to encapsulate internal exceptions
   and present them in a form suitable for various clients.
 * Code Execution Context Preservation: WCF client can alter its behavior based
   on the state of the service when the exception occurred.

CODE EXAMPLE: SERVICE EXCEPTION SHIELDING AND CLIENT BEHAVIOR CHANGE

Here are the C# code:

[ServiceContract]
public interface IMyService
{
    [OperationContract]
    string PotentiallyLongRunningOperation();
}

public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public string PotentiallyLongRunningOperation()
    {
        try
        {
            // Some operation that may throw an exception
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            throw new FaultException("An error occurred while processing the request.");
        }
    }
}

/// <summary>
/// WCF client showcase handling fault
/// </summary>
public class WcfClient
{
    public void CallServiceMethod(string endpointUrl)
    {
        using (ServiceProxy<IMyService> proxy = new ServiceProxy<IMyService>(endpointUrl))
        {
            proxy.Channel.PotentiallyLongRunningOperation();
        }
    }
}



BENEFITS OF USING EXCEPTION HANDLING AND FAULT SERVICE

 * Security: The service cannot be made vulnerable by exposing too much internal
   information.
 * Client Experience: Ensures that clients receive the correct and expected
   information from the service.

WCF offers several ways to consume RESTful web services, each tailored to
distinct requirements.


TECHNIQUES FOR CONSUMPTION

 1. ASP.NET Web API Client Libraries

    * WCF and ASP.NET Web API have a consistent model for creating RESTful
      services and consuming them, especially in .NET 4.5 and onward.

 2. ChannelFactory<T>

    * A simplified and direct approach, often used when more advanced WCF client
      features aren't necessary.

 3. HttpWebRequest

    * A more manual, low-level method that provides greater control over REST
      requests.

 4. ASP.NET AJAX and the ScriptManager

    * Gives a way to invoke web services asynchronously.


CODE EXAMPLE: ASP.NET WEB API CLIENT LIBRARIES

Here is the C# code

using (var client = new HttpClient())
{
    HttpResponseMessage response = await client.GetAsync("http://example.com/api/resource");
    if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
    {
        string jsonResult = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
        // Process result JSON
    }
    else
    {
        // Handle non-success status
    }
}

Implementing a custom message inspector in WCF provides fine-grained control
over messages being sent and received. This can be especially useful for message
logging, content manipulation, or custom security measures.


KEY COMPONENTS

 * Message Inspector: Analyzes and optionally modifies incoming and outgoing
   messages.
 * Endpoint Behavior: Associates the message inspector with the endpoint.


IMPLEMENTING THE CUSTOM MESSAGE INSPECTOR

The example below demonstrates a trace inspector that logs the message header
and the actions that were performed.

C#

Here is the C# code:

using System;
using System.ServiceModel;
using System.ServiceModel.Channels;
using System.ServiceModel.Description;
using System.ServiceModel.Dispatcher;

public class TraceMessageInspector : IDispatchMessageInspector
{
    public object AfterReceiveRequest(ref Message request, IClientChannel channel, InstanceContext instanceContext)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Received");
        return null;
    }

    public void BeforeSendReply(ref Message reply, object correlationState)
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Sent");
    }
}

[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Interface)]
public class TraceEndpointBehavior : Attribute, IEndpointBehavior
{
