WCF services offer a wide range of options to optimize for scalability and
handle varying levels of application load.


LOAD BALANCING

WCF uses Load Balancing to distribute client requests across multiple service
instances or machines.

LOAD BALANCING MODES IN WCF

 * Round-Robin: Each request is directed to the next available service instance
   or machine in a sequential manner.
 * Weighted Round Robin: This mode enables the assignment of different weights
   to service instances. The higher the weight, the more requests a service
   instance will handle in the rotation.

CONFIGURATION

Here's a sample configuration that enables load balancing:

<client>
  <endpoint address="http://example.com/MyService" binding="wsHttpBinding" 
  contract="MyService.IMyService" name="MyServiceEndpoint"/>
</client>



CONCURRENCY CONTROL

WCF services offer three primary modes for concurrency control:

 * Single: This mode processes one request at a time.
 * Multiple: Allows simultaneous request processing.
 * Reentrant: Useful for handling callbacks.

VERSIONING

WCF permits multiple service versions running simultaneously, making it easier
to roll out updates.


GLOBAL EXCEPTION HANDLING

By leveraging a global error handler, WCF architects can ensure proper exception
logging and propagation to clients, thereby maintaining application stability.

CODE EXAMPLE: IMPLEMENTING A GLOBAL EXCEPTION HANDLER

Here is the C# code:

[ServiceBehavior(IncludeExceptionDetailInFaults=true)]
public class MyService : IMyService
{
    public void MyOperation()
    {
        try
        {
            // Service operation logic
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            // Log exception
            throw new FaultException("An error occurred. Please try again.");
        }
    }
}

public class GlobalErrorHandler : IErrorHandler
{
    public bool HandleError(Exception error)
    {
        // Log the error
        return false;
    }

    public void ProvideFault(Exception error, MessageVersion version, ref Message fault)
    {
        // Replace the fault message with a standardized message
        var faultException = new FaultException("An unexpected error occurred. Please try again.");
        var message = faultException.CreateMessageFault();
        fault = Message.CreateMessage(version, message, faultException.Action);
    }
}



